{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_haiti_ver02/data/sn83030214/00175039740/1910112801/0585.xml":{"full_text":"MONDAY, New-1) ork dribune NOVEMBER 28. 1910.\n\nBerra\nJ. J. HILL PREDICTS\nWORLD DEPRESSION\n12\nRailroad Man Says Next Year\nWill See Universal Hard\nTimes in Trade.\nNO WORK FOR THOUSANDS\nThinks Americans Too Extrava\ngant and That Too Much of\nTheir Capital Goes Into Non\nProductive Enterprises.\n[By Telegraph to The Tribune.)\nSt. Paul. Nov. 27.\u2014That the United States\nend the world, in fact, are about to har\nvest the fruits grown of extravagance,\nJ. J. Hill is absolutely positive. It is too\nlate to warn; the hour is now near, he savs.\n\u201cYWhy, when I told President Taft a few\ndays ago,\u201d said Mr. Hill, \u201cthat there would\nhe many thousands of men thrown out of\nemployment, he was almost incredulous of\nmy sincerity. But I am not making a\nguess. It will be a fact\u201d\nMr. Hill sai@ that the President \u201cis a\ngood fellow: he means well, but he has\nmade lots of mistakes.\n\u201cThe trouble with Mr. Taft,\u201d he contin\nwed, \u201cis that he lives in a political at\nmosphere. He can\u2019t get away from it. It\npervades Washington, and the President's\nviews of conditions are limited in a large\nmeasure Hy those who surround Lim.\u201d\n\u201c3Why not get business men to accept\noffice\u201d repeated Mr. Hill, in answer to a\nquestion.\n\u201cThat would be altogether impossible. A\nbusiness man could not remain in the po\nsition. His election could come about only\n+l'rouzgh the efforts of these supporting him,\nwhich would mean a besieging horde of\noflice seckers.\u201d\n\n\n\nMr. Hill declared that the American peo\nple were tco complacent. They spend too\nfreely, and are greatly jnclined to take a\nrosy view of things entirely unwarranted\nby \u00abcircumstances.\n\n\n\ni\nAmericans Too Extravagant.\n\n~Exiravagance is their great fault,\u201d said\nhe. \u201cWe have been wasting entirely too\nmuch in non-preductive undertakings. As\na tule we have been given 100 much to\nadornments. We have become obsessed\nwith \u2018the city beautiful\u2019 in municipal af\nfairs. We have followed like policies in the\nstate and natienal governments.\n\nJ\n\n\n\n\ni\ni\n\n\u201cBattleships, not only in this country, but\nalso abroad, are iliustrations of the ex\ntravagance in which the world has been\nplunged in the last two decades. The\nmoney for the construction of these has\nbeen withdrawn from commercial circles\nand almost as good as squandered, so far\nas there can be any tangible returns ob\nserved.\n\n\n\n\n7\n\n\u201cWe have gone to considerable expense\nto dig the Panama Canal. T presume now\nwe will have to fortify it. It's all very well\nto make appropriations for such purposes\u2014\nit's easy to contract debts\u2014but the real\ndifficulty arises when we come to get the\nmoney with which to make the payments,\n\n\ngi\n\u201cIn four years, from 1882 tro 189%, our fed\neral expenditures were $1,800,00000. For a\nsimilar period, from 1%4 to 1908, we spent\nabout $3,600,000,000. Yet we pay our iaxes\n&nd harp upon the high cost of living, and\neven in doing this we linger upon the brill\nfant prospects which we think the future\nholds in store for us. If a man buys a\nfarm and cultivates it he contributes to the\nmaterial wealth of society. If he permits\nthe land to lie idle he has subtracted\nfrom the general wealth by withdrawing\nhis money from commerce and investing\njt in a non-profitable enterprise. That\nserves best to illustrate our trend in all de\npartments of our government.\u201d\n\nen\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\ni\n\n\n\nl\ni\n\nFew New Enterprises.\n\nriser iming any intention of posing as a\ncalamity prophet. Ar. Hill insisted, how\n\u00abver, that it was not a guess, but an abso\nlute certainty as to what awaits the coun\ntrv next vear when business becomes dor\nmant. He pointed out that at present few\nnew enteryriscs are being planned. This,\nhe said, means suspersion of activities.\n\n\n\ni\nP.M.\n49\nis 35\ni i\n\u00a304\n\n\u201c10 vou hear of any generally systematic\nplans for improvements during the next\nyear?\u2019 he asked. \u201cThere are none. Fac\ntories, and other such enterprises, which\nsre productive in their mature and which\ncontribute 10 wealth, are not contempiated\nIv those who have the money to invest.\n\ni\ni\n\n\n\n\n\n*\u201cTlis means that those who have noth\ning to zeli but their time will be without\ncmplovmen\u00ae. There will have to be a shut\nting dorm of tlie mines because iron and\n\ncoa' aud other minerals that go into the\nproduction of commercial articles will not\nZe fu aemanl. The same might be said\nahout tie lumber business and other forms\nof aciiviiy. As a result of all this there\nWill be many thousands of people without\nemplerment.\n\n\ndi e\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\neT\n\nnr\n\ni\n\n\n{=F\nRailroad Curtailment.\n\u201cIn preparing our Great Northern orders\nfor mext year we find that we are going\nto need very few supplies. This is because\nwe are making no extensions, Last vear\nne ordered 245.000 tons of rails and had no\nsurplus. For the next year we will need\ncniy about 70.60% tons.\ni\n\ng\n\ni\nki\n\n{i\nj\n\u201c1 might repeat such illustrations in our\nbusiness, Last year we had to have 11.008\nnew freight cars. This year we shall need\nonly 3600. J.ast year we were compelled to\nequip a large number of passenger coaches:\nthis rear we shall need none. We ordered\nmore than three hundred engines last year.\nTwenty new ones wili be an abundance for\nnext season,\n\ni\noth ivee v\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\u201cOther business interests, of which 1\nhappen to know. are making no further\nprovisions looking toward improvements or\nextensions than we are. It is not because\nthey haven't the money, but because there\nare no inducements. considering public gen\ntiment and the business outlook, for them\nto invest in.\ni Eves ast We\nsens FORGOT.\n1\n\n\nfe\n\n\n\nTI\n\u201cThat will happen, d say, therefore is\n2 matter of ceriainty. Enterprise in all\nInes will come 10 a standstill, There will\nbe no progress. Many persons will have to\nchange aeir occupations and habits of\n\ni\ni\nni\n\nining.\u201d\nPARK'S SACRED COW WEEPS\n\nroc Tele=ranh to The Tribune.)\nNr A eT To ro\nSt. Paul. Nov. 2i.\u2014That the United States\nend the world, in fact, are about to har\nvest the fruits grown of extravagance,\nJ. J. Hin is absolutely positive. It is too\nlate to warn; the hour is now near, he savs.\n\u201cWhy, when I told President Taft a few\ndays ago,\u201d said Mr. Hill, \u201cthat there would\nhe many thousands of men thrown out of\nemployment, he was almost incredulous of\nmy sincerity. But I am not making a\nguess. It will be a fact\u201d\nMr. Hill sai@ that the President \u201cis a\ngood fellow: he means well, but he has\nmade iots of mistakes.\n\u201cThe trouble with Mr. Taft,\u201d he contin\nwed, \u201cis that he lives in a political at\nmosphere. He can\u2019t get away from it. It\npervades Washington, and the President's\nviews of conditions are limited in a large\nmeasure by those who surround Lim.\u201d\n\u201cWhy not get business men to accept\noffice\u201d repeated Mr. Hill, in answer to a\nquestion.\n\u201cThat would be altozether impossible. A\nbusiness man could not remain in the po\nsition. His election could come about only\ntl:rouzh the efforts of these supporting him,\nwhich would mean a besieging horde of\noflice seckers.\u201d\nMr. Hill declared that the American peo\nple were tco complacent. They spend 190\nfreely, and are greatly jnclined to take a\nrosy view of things entirely unwarranted\n\"Fo TT yy oy\nAmericans Too Extravagant.\n~Exiravagance is their great fault,\u201d said\nhe. \u201cWe have been wasting entirely too\nmuch in non-preductive undertakings. As\na tule we have been given 100 much to\nadornments. We have become obsessed\nwith \u2018the city beautiful\u2019 in municipal af\nfairs. We have followed like policies in the\nstate and natienal governments.\n\u201cBattleships, not only in this country, but\nalso abroad, are iliustrations of the ex\ntravagance in which the world has been\nplunged in the last two decades. The\nmoney for the construction of these has\nbeen withdrawn from commercial circles\nand almost as good as squandered, so far\nas there can be any tangible returns ob\nserved.\n\u201cWe have gone to considerable expense\nto dig the Panama Canal. T presume now\nwe will have to fortify it. It's all very well\nto make appropriations for such purposes\u2014\nit's easy to contract debts\u2014but the real\ndifficulty arises when we come to get the\nmoney with which to make the payments,\n\u201cIn four years, from 1882 tro 189%, our fed\neral expenditures were $1,800,00000. For a\nsimilar period, from 1%4 to 1908, we spent\nabout $3,600,00,000. Yet we pay our iaxes\n&nd harp upon the high cost of living, and\neven in doing this we linger upon the brill\nfant prospects which we think the future\nholds in store for us. If a man buys a\nfarm and cultivates it he contributes to the\nmaterial wealth of society. If he permits\nthe land to lie idle he has subtracted\nfrom the general wealth by withdrawing\nhis money from commerce and investing\njt in a non-profitable enterprise. That\nserves best to illustrate our trend in all de\nrartments of our government.\u201d\nFew New Enterprises.\nYrise\u2019r iming any intention of posing as a\ncalamity prophet. Ar. Hill insisted, how\n\u00abver, that it was not a guess, but an abso\nInte ccrtainty as to what awaits the coun\ntrv next vear when business becomes dor\nmant. He pointed out that at present few\nnew enterprises are being planned. This,\nhe said, means suspersion of activities.\n\u201c10 vou hear of any generally systematic\nplans for improvements during the next\nyear?\u2019 he asked. \u201cThere are none. Fzac\ntories, and other such enterprises, which\nore productive in their mature and which\ncontribute to wealth, are not contempiated\nI'v these who have the money to invest.\n*\u201cTlis means that those who have noth\nng to sell but their time will be without\nemplovmen\u00ae. There will have to be a shut\nting damn of the mines because iron and\ncoa' and other minerals that go into the\nproduction of commercial articles will not\nZe fu aemanl The same might be said\nabout tie lumber business and other forms\nof activity. As a result of all this there\nWill he many thousands of people without\nornament\nRziiroad Curtailment.\n\u201cIn preparing our Great Northern orders\nfor mext vear we find that we are going\nto need very few supplies. This is because\nwe are making no extensions. Last vear\nwe ordered 245.000 tons of rails and had no\nsurplus. For the next year we will need\noniy about 70.600 tons.\n\u201c1 might repeat such illustrations in our\nbusiness. Last year we had to have 11.000\nnew freight cars. This year we shall need\nonly 3.60. J.ast year we were compelled to\nequip a large number of passenger coaches:\nthis year we shall need none. We ordered\nmore than three hundred engines last year.\nTwenty new ones wili be an abundance for\nnext season,\n\u201cOther business interests, of which I\nhappen to know. are making no further\nprovisions looking toward improvements or\nextensions than we are. It is not because\n1they haven't the money, but because there\nare no inducements. considering public gen\ntiment and the business outlook, for them\n10 invest in.\n\u201cWhat will happen, d say, therefore is\n2 matter of certainty. Enterprise in all\nInes will come 10 a standstill, There will\nbe no progress. Many persons will have to\nchenge oeir occupations and habits of\nLiving.\u201d\nPARKS SACRED COW WEEPS\n\nCrly a Bad Cold, but Still Keeper\n\u2018\u201c*Bill\u2019\u2019 Snyder Worries.\nE\nATS\ni THUR\nTHURS\nPARK'S SACRED COW WEEPS\n\n\nThe sacred cow in the Central Park\nn.enagerie has a cold. When twenty or\n1Liity successive sneezes of a loudness that\njosseth understanding were heard yester\ncay morning issuing from the Louse occu\n1ied by this animal, one of the keepers\nliked into the abode of the cow and saw\ntears coming from her eyes. Another sneeze\nTf llowed, and then the keeper made for\nthe animals\u2019 book of household remedies\nin the library of \u201cBill\u201d Snyder, the head\nkeeper.\n\n\n\n\n\n\ni tO\n\n\n\n\n\nJ\n100.\n\n8\nThere was not 2a word zbout sacred cows\ni. the book. There were lion and hippo\nsday\nwi VAT LACE\nEDDINGER\nGEN i\n\nmzladies galore, but never a mention of\ngh sacred beasts. Meanwhile, the ordi\nnarily demure cow waxed wroth, and the\ngieater became her temper the more fre\nGlen were her sneezes.\nI}\n\u00ab6\nWien she retired, l2te in the evening, the\ncold was better, but there was \u00abven then\nan occasional vielent emission of zir from\nher OSC\n\ni\n86:30\nI\nACAINST STATE CONSERVATICN\nr\u2014\nDaily Mat. M\u2014\u2014\u2014\nPhoenix, Ariz., Nov. 27. \u2014State conserva\ntion \u00abf public lands was defeated yester\ndav in the constitutional convention, which\nby an everwhelminig vote favored an\namendment io enable the state to dispose\nof the lands as it mav see fit under the re\n@trictions of tne enabling acl\n|g\n\n\n1\n\na\nCC CART 12 VLAD OID AND STII GOING STRONG.\nUNCLE SAM. 134 YEARS OLD AND STILL GOING STRONG.\nAIDS DISPOSSESSED FAMILY CENEDA| BIICINFGS\nAIDS DISPOSSESSED FAMILY\nFriendly Real Estate Man Gives\nHome to Brownsville Folk.\nA crowd of curious persons grouped\nthemselves zbout a man and a woman\nand six small children on the sidewalk\nopposite No. 17 Chester street, Brooklyn,\nvesterday efternoon. Near the curb lay\na heap of furniture, telling a tale of hard\nand pinching poverty. The man and his\nwife and their children were poorly\nGressed, and all shivered in the cold\nwind. They had been dispossessed.\nTwo years ago Isaac Regel was a\nwealthy real estate dealer of Brownsville,\nworth not less than $65,000, Reverses\ncame, and Regel saw all his fortune\nswept away.\nAbraham, one of the children, had\nbeen taken to St. Mary's Hospital earlier\nin the afternoon, suffering from emacia\ntion. \u201cStarvatien,\u201d the ambulance sur\ngeon said.\nWhile the family were standing hope\nlessly in the street Marcus Palley, a real\nestate agent and an old friend of Regel,\nwalked down the street. He ordered\nthat the family\u2019s effects be taken to No.\n1821 Pitkin avenue, which he owns.\nRegel and his family again have a home.\nWILL FIGHT OFF FOR A TIME\nBrinckerhoff Heirs to Renew It\nRefore Supreme Court.\nThe much talked of contest over the will\nof Mrs. Mary E. Brinckerhoff, of Hastings\non-the-Hudson, who left between $5,000,\n000 and $7,000,000, and which is scheduled\nto be continued before Surrogate Millard\n2t White Plains to-day, it was learned yes\nterday, will be dropped temporarily. It\nis understood that the heirs are ic allow\nthe will to be probated by the Surrogate\nand that they will continue their fight in\nthe Supreme Court.\n\n\nAn action to set aside the probate will\nbe started, and the 125 heirs who are\nfigkting the will, contending that Mrs.\nPrinckerhoff was incompetent to make a\nwili and that undue influence was exer\ncised over her by c\u00e9rtain relatives, will\ntren produce their evidence. Only about\neight heirs, mostly cousins, nephews and\nnieces of Mrs. Brinckerhoff, inherit the\nmajor portion of the estate of millions,\nwhile all the other next of kin are cut off\nwithout a cent.\n\n\nLined up with the heirs who benefit and\nwho will fight to sustain the will are a\ndozen servants who received large bequests\nfor their faithful service during the many\nvears they were in Mrs. Brinckerhoff's em\nploy. When the will is admitted te probate\nthe New York Life Insurance Company\nwil! be the sole executor and trustee, as\nthe other executor named in the will is\ndead.\nCONDUCTOR LIKED GUMDRCPS\n\nSwears Man Who Gave Him Some\nLikewise Picked His Nickel Pocket.\nA young man who said he was Jacob\nSchiff, though the police said he was Sam\nuel Rothenberg, was held in $1,500 bail for\nthe grand jury on a charge of grand lar\nceny by Magistrate Murphy in the Jeffer\nscn Market police court yesterday morning.\n\nHe was arrested after a chase through\nTrion Square Park by Patrolman Harry\nMcCrossen, of Brooklyn, a passenger on\ntne car from which the young man jumped,\nafter a tussle with the conductor.\nWilliam Robb, conductor of the car, told\nTagistrate Murphy the prisoner stood on\nthe rear platform and handed a bag of\ngumdrops to him.\n\u201cI took one,\u201d said Robb, \u201cand thanked\nhim. He said, \u2018Oh, take more than that\u2019\nthen took some in one hand and put his\nother hand in my coat pocket, where I keep\nmy nickels. As he drew his hand out I\ngrabbed it.\u201d\nOLD HOTEL MAN A SUICIDE\nLouis D. Corsor, Well Known in Queens\nCounty, Shoots Himself.\nIouis D. Corsor, sixty-four years old,\nformerly proprietor of the Waveriy House,\nin Far Rockaway, shot himself through the\nLead yesterday with a revolver at his home,\nNo. 81 Flushing avenue, Jamaica, Long\nIsland. \"He died four hours later in St.\nMary's Hospital.\n\nCorsor retired from business twelve vears\nago, and was considered wealthy, He had\nbeen prominent among Deniocrats in\nQueens County, but had never held office,\nYesterday morning Corsor sent his wife\nout of the room for a newspaper. He muf\nfled his revolver in a pillow, which he\nplaced against his head, and fired a shot\nthat penetrated his left temple. It is be\nlieved that despondency over the state of\nhis health and the death of a daughter\nthree weeks ago caused Corsor to shoot\nhimself.\nTO RESUME BERMUDA TRIPS\n\u2018Slashing of Rates Expected\u2014A. I. Cul\nver Heads Reorganized Line.\nAnnouncement was made yesterday by\nthe Bermuda Atlantic Line that it had\nchartercd the cruising yacht Oceana, of\nthe Hamburg-American Line, and would\nstart a regular service to Bermnda this\nwinter, with a minhinum rate of $26 for the\nexcursion.\nThe Bermuda Atlantic Line discontinued\nits service a vear azo, when it operated\nwith the steamship Prince George in com\npetition with the Quebec Line.\n-_\nThere was a <lashing of rates then, and\nit is expected that the Jow rate of the Ber\nmuda Atlantic Line will force the Quebeo\nand the Royal Mail Steam Packet Company\nto come down from their present mininium\nof $36. A {i Cuiver, formerly of the Diela\nware Hudson Railroad, is the new presi\ngent of the reorganized Bermuda Atlantic\nae.\nGENERAL BUSINESS SLOW\nEditor of Ae Industries\u201d\nGives Four Reasons.\nFAVORS TARIFF COMMISSION\nMajority of Manufacturers Be\nlieve Question Is Cause of\nNational Irritation.\nEditor of \u201cAmerican Industries\u201d\nGives Four Reasons.\nFAVORS TARIFF COMMISSION\nMajority of Manufacturers Be:\nlieve Question Is Cause of\nNational Irritation.\nPresent trade conditions in the United\nStates are comprehensively considered in\nthe December issue of \u201cAmerican Indus\ntries,\u201d the monthly magazine conducted in\nthe interest of the National Association of\nManufacturers. It presents tables based\nupon recent reports from the three thou\nsand members of the association, showing\nin percentage figures, tabulated under\n\u201cpoor,\u201d *\u201c\u2018fair,\u201d \u201cgood\u201d and \u201cexcellent\u201d\nthe current conditions in many important\nindustries and the prospects in 1211,\nThere are also carried a large number\nof letters from members, offering sugges\ntions for improving the trade situation,\nand an article \u201cWhat Is the Matter with\nBusiness?\u2019 by the editor, Henry Harrison\nLewis, analyzing the condition reports and\nthe members\u2019 suggestions. John Kirby, jr.,\npresident of the association, also contrib\nutes an article on the significance of the\nelection of this month in relation to the\ncountry\u2019s industries.\nMr. Lewis, in discussing tabulated re\nturns and the suggestions and opinions of\nthe manufacturers, says, in part:\nA thoughtful analysis of the tables will\nreveal that while business as a whole is\nslow, certain industries show marked stag\nnation, while others are fairly good and a\nfew enjoy a satisfactory degree of pros\nperity. The average, however, is below\nnormal.\nBusiness, and that means practically the\ncountry, is suffering from several ills.\nThese can tentatively be classified as (1)\nnational irritation, (2) speculation, (3) in\nternal dissension and (4) lack of confidence.\nThe first, national irritation, which has af\nfected all business alike, arises from an\n\u2018undue, unnecessary and harmful political\nagitation.\nAnother cause for this national irritation\nwhich has worked such commercial unrest\nand injury is the failure of men of affairs\nand national leaders to remove the tariff\nfrom political influence and control. This\nis the opinion, at least, of a majority of\nthose members of the National Association\nof Manufacturers who replied to the circu\nlar requesting information. In passing, it\nmay be well to understand that nowhere is\nthe need of an independent tariff commis\nsion more clearly recognized than among\nthe manufacturers who are popularly sup\nposed to be the actual beneficiaries of high\nprotection.\nThe second national ill is speculation,\nwhich, according to the reports received,\nmeans not only stock speculation, but to\neven greater extent business speculation,\nor unwise, careless and practically repre\nhensible gambling on future demand. The\neager desire following the panic of 197 to\nholster up business, and the <hildlike hope\nthat prosperity was bound to return in the\nnear future, undoubtedly caused a great\nmany concerns to take desperate chances.\nInternal differences or dissension between\nindustries is the third ill, as indicated by\nthe association's reports. The most im\nportant phase of this classification by far\nis the railway rates problem.\nA divicion of the industries into threes\nclasses, viz.: Depressed industries, indus\ntries doing a fair business and industries\nenjoying prosperity, according to the re\nports that have been received, shows that\nthe first classification, namely, depressed\nindustries, made up of pig iron and steel\nbiliets, railway iron and steel, machinery,\niron and woodworking; lumber, general\ntools and hardware, vehicles and leather,\nconsists of those directly or indirectly econ\nnected with railroad construction or main\ntenance.\nThey probably represent 50 per cent of\nthe nation\u2019s industries. and it is these in\ndustries which report their sales as poor,\ntheir collections slight, their present con\nditions as poor and the future discourag\ning.\nIt is significant that in the whole volume\nof replies received from the members of\nthe National Association of Manufacturers\nnot one was adverse to a fair increase of\nrates: on the other hanf, a great number\nrecommended a speedy adjustment with\nfairness to the railways.\nPresident Kirby, in discussing the elec\ntion results, which he views as a rebuke\nfor the \u2018new nationalism,\u201d devotes him\nself mainly to the tariff and the labor ques\ntion. In his opinion, \u201cwhatever dissatis\nfaction exists over the Payne-Aldrich tariff\nlaw, when analyzed, is not so much with\nthe law itself as with the manner in which\nit was created and the refusal of Congress\nto heed the demand of the business inter\nests of the country for the creation of a\npermanent tariff commission.\u201d\niesi1aennt Dat yy, 101 isSCUssSIing ine eljec\ntion results, which he views as a rebuke\nfor the \u2018new nationalism,\u201d devotes him\nself mainly to the tariff and the labor ques\ntion. In his opinion, \u201cwhatever dissatis\nfaction exists over the Payne-Aldrich tariff\nlaw, when analyzed, is not so much with\nthe law itself as with the manner in which\nit was created and the refusal of Congress\nto heed the demand of the business inter\nests of the country for the creation of a\npermanent tariff commission.\u201d\nEIGET TAKEN IN RAIDS HELD\nMore than 160 Others Arrested in Al\nleged Gambling Houses Freed.\nTwenty-six of the seventy-nine prisoners\ntaken in 2 raid bv Deputy Commissioner\nDriscoll on an alleged gambling house\nknown as the Alecto Club, in 42d street,\nnear Third avenue, on Saturday, were ar\nreigned yesterday before Magistrate Krotel\nin the Yorkville police court He dis\ncharged all but six.\nJohn Daly, of No. 20607 Bryant avenue;\nJohn Morrison, of No. 380 Lexington ave\nnue, were held in $1,000 bail each as\nproprietors of a gambling house, and the\ntour others were beld in similar bond as\ncommon gamblers. The examination of all\nvill take place on Wednesday afternoon.\nin the nizht court on Saturday fifty-three\nol the prisoners were released,\nCharged with being common gamblers,\ntwe men, who said they were John Dunn\nand Charles Friedland, who were taken in\na raid on an alleged gambling house in\n126th street, near Eighth avenue, on Sat\nurday night, were arraigned in the Harlem\ncourt, where Magistrate Corrigan held\nthem each in $500 bail for examination on\nThursday. Seventy-two other mien arrest\ne! In the same raid were discharged in\nthe night t on Saturday.\nURGES INSURANCE REFORM\nMerchants\u2019 Association for Tax\nand Commission Reductions.\n\nThe Merchants' Association of NEW ZH\nIn a letter to the legislative investigating\ncommittee, made public yesterday, urges\nthat body to make a theroush inquiry into\nthe commissions paid by fire insurance com\npanies to their agents for securing business,\nand also suggests that the taxation of such\ncompanies might be greatly reduced.\nThese taxes, says Frank R. Chambers,\nthe chairman of the association's committee\non insurance, impose neavy and possibly\nunnecessary burden on the fire insurance\ncompanies, which they naturally turn over\ncost of\nto policyholders as a part of the\nrunning their business.\nRemedial legislation to modif\nthese special taxes is suggested bY the\nMerchants\u2019 Association. and they want the\nlegislative investigating committee to lay\na basis for new legislation by 2 thorough\nInquiry on these two points.\n\u201cIn the city of New York,\u201d\nter to Edwin A. Merritt, jr.\nof the investigating committee,\nor 10 per cent brokerage is paid to agents\nupon premiums derived from the central\nbusiness district, increasing to 2 per cent\nin the case of residences, churches, ete. In\nother parts of the state many companies\npay flat commissions to agents of 15 per\ncent, others pay 20 per cent or 25 per cent\nand an additional commission up to 10 per\ncent contingent upon the profits on business\nsecured.\u201d\n\u201cThese large commissions,\u201d the Mer\nchants\u2019 Association writes, \u2018\u2018are, of course.\nincluded by the companies in the cost of\ndoing business, which total cost must come\nout of the aggregate premiums derived from\ninsurers, and the scale of compensation to\nsalesmen or agents is materially higher\nthan that which usually prevails In other\nbranches of business.\u201d Further, it is point\ned out that the cost of selling insurance is\nconsiderably less, or should be, than the\ncost of selling merchandise.\n\u201cThis association,\u201d the letter continues,\n\u201ccalls attention to the heavy burden of spe\ncial taxation laid upon insurance compa\nnies in this state, but actually borne by\ninsurers, whereby the cost of insurance is\nmaterially increased.\u201d\nOrdinary taxes represent the payment to\nthe government of a part of the profit de\nrived from the economic use of wealth,\nthey say, but taxes derived from an in\nsurance fund represent an addition to the\nburden upon a community imposed by the\ndestruction of wealth, \u201cIt is wholly unjust\nthat the fund exacted from the community\nto distribute the burden of destruction\nShould be increased by government exac\nion.\u201d\nCiting figures on the taxes exacted by\nthe state as a corporation tax to cover the\ncost of government regulation and super\nvision of insurance companies, the letter\nsays that under Section 187 of the tax law\nthe state derived during the last fiscal\nvear $1,236,97353, with an additional fund\nobtained from companies not incorporated\nin this state but doing business here of\n$427,074 40, whereas the total cost of con\nducting the State Insurance Department\nduring the same period was about $226,000.\nThe state therefore derived a net revenue\nfrom the taxation of insurance companies\nabout $1,739,000, because in addition to the\ny or abolish\nsays the let\nthe chairman\n\u00ab5 per cent\ntaxes mentioned above there was an addi\ntional special tax of 2 per cent on Bross\npremiums levied by municipalities, from\nwhich in the citv of New York alone the\nircome was $301,67705 during the same\nperiod.\n\u201cThe premium rates charged by insurance\ncompanies,\u201d the letter continues, \u2018\u2018repre\nsent not only the amount necessary to meet\nfire losses, plus a reasonable profit upon the\ncapital of the companies, but also repre\ncent and are based upon the expense 0]\nconducting business, and of this expense\nthe item of taxation is a large and im\nportant one. This excess of taxation is\nsimply a burden upon calamity.\u201d\nThe legislative investigating committe\nwill resume its public inquiry to-morrow\nmorning, but it is unlikely that the subjec!\nof insurance will be taken up again then\nbecause the announced plans are to pursue\nto a finish the inquiry into legislative cor\nruption in connection with the activities\nof the lobby which appeared in opposition\nto the anti-racetrack gambling laws passed\n{n 1908. With that subject cleaned up, the\ncommittee will turn oem to its fire Insur\n1\nance inquiry, upon w ich an opening was\nmade at the last two sessions befoxe the\nmia lrecoivine recess,\nMARINE INTELLIGENCE.\nNI ATO RE ALMANAC.\nTR TH Epa\nMINIATURE ALMANAC.\nSunrise, 7:00: sunset, 4:35; moon rises, 23:52;\nian HME PIR\nHICH WATER.\nrr RE ent SEC 4 Ser